\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Very well. Very well
. Very seldom we quarrelled. Very very seldom. And it would be - if it would be we quarrelled it would be something - over something very trifling. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Was there one you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well you see, the last two home, that was my 
sister and I. We were close because we were the last two at home. The others had got married. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about when you were little, before you left school, was there one of the family then that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No, we were ve
ry close to each other, all of us. Very closely knit family - we were. 'Cos we were six boys - six girls and three boys you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 There wasn't one that you were more friendly with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, no, no, it was always the youngest that was the favourite. Yo
u know, the youngest, and - but - and - but no, it was funny my mother - thought when - she'd had enough children well they believed I think in those days it was funny that there was no talk about birth control was there. And the - when - she'd had - Rhia
n
non, that'd be the youngest now, and she'd had - she had had enough she didn't want any more, and when she discovered - that she was forty - four I think - or forty - forty-three I think she was, forty-three when she was going to have another baby she rea
l
ly was terribly upset. And she didn't want to go out. She was ashamed to go out walking. And of course we - my father was very fond of taking us for long walks up to Penrhys mountain we used to walk miles. We even used to walk over the mountains right dow
n into Porth to see an auntie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And she wouldn't go out with you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
She would come, she had to come, my father - yes, yes, yes, she would. She was a wonderful woman, oh she was brave woman, oh but she didn't want - but isn't it funny, she didn'
t want him. And then we should - we didn't keep him for long you see. Though he lived you see to - oh, he had a marve}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6695053\charrsid12417786 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
lous career before him, he - he had first class honours. Oh dear, I've forgotten what they were no. English, history.
