\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 If I can remember roughly when they used to have their pay on Saturdays in those days, that's right, we used to have about a penny. Penn
y, I think it was only about a penny. No, no more than a penny.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would you have that every week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did anyone outside the home help your mother to look after the house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - we 
had a - there was a family - Auntie Hannah, and Auntie Maggie. There were - there was a family of five daughters. And they used to - and Auntie Hannah - and Auntie Maggie used to come to us. Oh and they were angels.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They weren't relatives actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Only friends. I called them Auntie, and they used to come every Tuesday - Auntie Maggie first, she was the first, Auntie - Gwen came - Auntie Hannah came later, when Auntie Maggie failed to come. Auntie Maggie came - to wash for my mother every Tuesda
y. And my mother would do all the ironing and - we had a brass rod there, oh - and you would see all these things here, and everybody that used to visit us used to love looking at the - what my mother could iron. She was a beautiful ironer. Well that Aunt
i
e Maggie - failed now, she had oh, very bad chest. Auntie Hannah now came next, the other Auntie. Bit older than her. And oh she was lovely. She was - kind to us and we could do - we could do what we liked with her, you know. And she used to read to us an
d things like that, but you see the big thing in ours you have to sit down and read books, read books.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did these two come just for the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 For the day. And my - that's right, my father had bookcase like that. My sister still got it in - Llandoch
 Street. And do you know, that bookcase was full of books. English and Welsh. And my father was such a terror for buying books that my mother used to get really cross.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 It was only to help your mother to wash that these people came?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Suppose she was ill}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6695053\charrsid12417786  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 or confined to bed, how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh well - well these came you see, Auntie Maggie or Auntie Hannah, they used to stay the week then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember what happened when one of your younger brothers or sisters was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I can only remember - I don't remember, only Deiniol the youngest being born you see and I should remember but I don't recollect.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember when he was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, I remember it quite well and we were very upset becau
se we weren't willing my mother was going to have another baby, and she didn't want him. She didn't want him. Because - oh yes, my mother was forty-five years of age you see. And we knew she didn't want him. And isn't it funny, we - we weren't allowed to 
keep him see after. Isn't it funny.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember what happened when he was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
I remember my brother, my eldest brother Meredith, being told my mother had been ill and not being able to get up from - in this bedroom, we had nice big rooms i
n our house. Not being able to get up. And - she'd had a new bed then too, this new bed. And it was not all the brass - the black and the - brass but it was green, lovely green, I can see that now. And - my father getting us out of bed and telling my brot
h
er to go and get Nurse Gilson. She lived not far away. Good long walk mind but - it wasn't terribly far. And telling him to go and fetch Nurse Gilson. Oh - and we were so upset to think that she was going to have another baby. We were really crying you kn
ow. We didn't want her to have another baby. We thought she'd had enough without having any more. When - and funny enough she didn't want him you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did somebody come in to look after her then when she was in bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They were with her, the - the same two you see, the same sisters. Sister - Auntie Hannah.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They'd look after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh they'd look after us. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember what happened that day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, oh yes, the baby being brought in and - seeing it washed in front of the
 fire you know. Oh yes, yes, yes. And I can remember vividly the little baby dying. That had this convulsion, this Mary Tydfil. She was named after Aunt Mary Fenwich and Tydfil, my Aunt Tydfil, the nurse. And - because my grandfather had been down for a h
o
liday from Cardiganshire and he said to my mother, os bydd - ohno, I'm coming - I'm wrong now - the last one this was, Deiniol. He said to my grandmother, osbydd y babi hyn yn bachgen fiam galw ef yn Einiol oherwydd John I eni yn Llanddeiniol. And that's 
a
n interesting story about my family. About Llanddeiniol. How we became Eglwys Bresbyteried Cymru. My grandfather - was one of three - gardeners - to - an Army officer, I can't remember a name, perhaps it'll come to my mind later. He was - he was a - a - g
a
rdener in - a Stad Abermad, Cardiganshire you see, Abermad was the name of the estate, and they lived in the houses on the estate, because they were - oh, miles of - of an estate and they did all the - garden. And - anyway the Wywigiad of - what would it 
b
e, 18 - 05 is it. Look up - you have my - you have my - now then. 1875 was it. You ask Maudwyn what it was after Dwyigiad. And one of them said to the others - I don't know, that was in Llandeiniol and - where did they have to go? Oh - I've forgotten the 
n
ame of the place now. Goginan. So they went. And they thought it was great. It was in Goginan but that's not the name of the chapel. I must find out that, see if I've got that written down somewhere. Oh dear, what was the name of the chapel, it wasn't Gog
i
nan, it wasn't as far as Goginan. And they enjoyed that Dywigiad, there was - oh, dear, dear, what's his name, Evan Roberts was in his Holi liamow you know, and they got back home that night and - he was waiting for them. Their Boss, Captain so and so. An
d
 he said, ddim moen gweld chwi. He gave them the sack because they went to the Dywigiad. That was a terrible thing wasn't it? Well, broken hearted of course. Like they had all had families you see. My grandfather. My - Uncle Edward that is in Canada and m
y father were the two children you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Whatever did they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Dad, Uncle Edward, what's the other one? Didn't know what to do so they said well, my father apparently - my grandfather apparently said, well - to his wife, Ann, mae rhaid i mi fynd 
I chwilio am wyith, ond y peth cyntaf yw chwilio am dy i fyw ynddo. Rwyn mynd a d'nid wyf fi yn dod n'ol tan fi findio ty a mae rhaid cael ty, he said, a fyddau'n findio gwaith weyn. He walks - all the way from Abermad right through to Goginan, couldn't f
i
nd a house in Goginan anywhere, do you know Goginan? Couldn't find a house in Goginan anywhere, and then he looks at the mountain and thinks to himself like that. He says - he walks up the hill from Goginan, right 'til he comes to the top, down now into C
w
mrheidol. And when he came down into Cwmrheidol he saw an empty house, and there was a little bit of a barn in it. And there was a toilet a field away, from the corner. And then he thought, well now who owns this. Well below it there was a farm, big farm,
 
called Troed Rhiw Las. So he goes down to this farm and asks - who was the owner of this - bit of property. So they told him, now I don't remember whether they were the owners of it or what. But he found out however who owned it. And he took it, on rent o
f
 course, and then - he stands and he looks over the valley - to Aberffrwd. There's that railway fach you know, going up there, Aberffrwd and there was a chapel there. Now the church - was in Penllwyn, so he said to my - he said to himself, well - bydd rha
i
d i ni mynd i'r capel ne, gallau byth cerdd cerdded tri milltir a hanner, tair mill tir a hanner i'r - i'r Benllwyn, he said. Rhaid i ni fynd i'r capel yn aberffwd. And the following Sunday that he went with her - two children, or three there were, three,
 
that's right, with the three children to Aberffrwd - and in the years to come he became - a deacon there. And he also had been buried there, and all the family have been buried in that cemetery. And that's how we became a Presbyterian - all because he'd h
ad the sack from work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby in Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 None at all. No relatives. No, no, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents have any friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Lots of friends. Oh lots of friends, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Where would they see them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Well my father you see was a - was - used to meet so many people in his work. And my - but two special friends they had - were Tommy - Davis and his wife, dash it, I've forgotten here name now. Forgotten her name, but there was Tommy Davis, 
and why they became friends - they were big Raccobites. A}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6695053\charrsid12417786 nd every years - they went away}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
 to conferences together. All up to Kilmarnock in Scotland - and - and I - did I tell you that, he used to say - looking round at Bobbie Burns on everything. Mawredd an
wyl John Back, gallai ti feddwl y Bobbie Burns yw Iesu Grist y lle yma. This was this man from Porth. Oh God knows his name, I think he was a deacon Cararierporth then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would your mother be friends with them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh, they used to come regularly, Mr
s Davis. But they only had one child you see, and they could come to us, we never went up to their house but it was - and this Gwyndri -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would they come often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 This Gwyndridd - I now - I don't even know whether he's alive today but his sister is alive you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They came to visit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes, always, never - never went to Ferndale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your mother have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Nothing special. She - no, I don't think so. She worked in a - when she came South first she worked i
n a big big - stores, grocery stores in Ferndale, oh I've forgotten the name of it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But when you were a little girl your mother wouldn't have any friends of her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No, no. Oh except the friends that were living in the street you see, the street friends. Yes, and the chapel friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would she go to their homes or would they come to your house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well it was mostly they would come to bur house because I mean we were all the children there you see and - and these little friends di
dn't have little children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would your father have separate friends or the same friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 The Raccobites he had, oh yes, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes. Casually, casual - except for Tommy Davis and his wife that always came you see. Always came regular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Once a week was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, I wouldn't say it was once a week but they came regularly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh cup of tea. My mother made all her own bread you see.
 We could carry them - a long way to the baker, one under each arm and one in front. The owner of the bakers and his wife and she would - and she adored my father, absolutely adored him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would you say that the friends invited into the house were your mother's friends or your father's friends?
