\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in this time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one class and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Not in a place like Tylorstown, there was no cause for it I don't think. No, I don't think so. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What class would you think you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 The working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And you think everybody in Tylorstown was the same class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes. We belonged to the working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Well I thought - all the people did, the only thing you - you felt that the doctors - you see, were - a bit above you but nobody else, we didn't consider our preachers you see, ministers of the Gospel, and the doctors, you had to l
ook up to them but there was nobody else that you considered any - you didn't used to consider them better than you either. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, never. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about the doctor or the minister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh and the doctors were friendly with us you see, friendly family. Very nice people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You weren't brought up to treat them differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you show respect in some way or would your brothers touch their cap to anybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Don't remember that you see. Don't remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Was there anyone you called sir or master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6695053\charrsid12417786 Do you remember any}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 one showing respect to your parents in that way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, I don't, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 In Tylorstown who would you consider the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well I would say - the doctors and the ministers. And - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who did you say were the most important people in Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh, the doctors and the preachers. And - and these friends, we thought they were very important.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Because they - they - they - well I suppose they were people in business mostly you see or - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And he was a J.P.?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why do you think they were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't know, I never - didn't - never thought of - I suppose because they were somebody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about the shopkeepers, who would they associate with in Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well they were all chapel people. And all friendly with chapel people, '
cos there was Arthur Davie now, Arthur David Jones. His father was the - had a big - he had - wait a bit now - he had a big - shop where he sold clothes, and - a milliner. They - they used to employ the milliner you see, to make hats. And - and her name w
a
s Miss Bries, she came - I don't know from what part of the world, but she was a Miss Bries and I can remember now as if it was yesterday having a beautiful big crinoline hat with lovely little rosebuds - and beautiful ribbons all round this hat, which sh
e would make with her own hands, and that was in the - shop where Arthur Davie - was living you see, 'cos his father was the Post Master.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who would they be friendly with in the village then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 All of us, all of us chapel people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Chapel people were friendly with other chapel people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Yes. That's right. Oh yes. And then you see Doctor Phillips, there was a milliner in this - in this Post Office, in the - in the shop part of it and he - courted this this milliner, see. And she was a - well - 
let's see now - she wasn't the milliner, wait a bit, it was the other one. Yes, he courted a milliner but he jilted her. That's right, he jilted this milliner - and he married - another lady, now I can't - can't remember - I must ask Mr Berryif he remembe
r
s - he married a very tall smart lady. Oh she was handsome. She was really beautiful, and she loved children, but she never had any of her own. But she used to be - Arolygessy festri, for always. And we children loved her. And she was kind to us. But what
 
was the most important thing we liked her for - because Doctor Phillips would be away every other Sunday preaching you see, and she would take us - girls to tea. To the Manse - wait a minute now - Galanth Road. Glanth Road. And we used to go down there to
 tea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How many of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
About five of us. And do you know - we used to love to play hide and seek, because it was a lovely house to play hide and seek, it was a big house. Upstairs and downstairs and she used to let us do what we liked there. And
 I can see her now, anyway - she had a - she was taken - suddenly taken ill - and she had appendicitis. And took her to London to sea a specialist, well we didn't know what appendicitis was in those days you know. Didn't know, never heard of it. Took her 
t
o London because of this pain that she had in her side. And saw a specialist. And the doctor there said that she'd appendicitis, something new. And he would operate. So he operated on her. When she came - back, wait a bit now - she died. That's right, she
 
- she died in London. So - she comes homes, I can remember as if it was yesterday, came to chapel the Sunday after she - had died, been buried you see and cried in the pulpit. He sobbed his heart out. Oh we were sorry for him. And we were sorrier because 
we had lost a good friend you know in Mrs Phillips.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What sort of people would you say went to the church there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Chapel you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Was there a church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes, English church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who went there, what people in Tylorstown would go to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
There were people in our street, there was a person living next - two doors down from us who went regularly to church. Until last year she was still alive.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What sort of people in Tylorstown would go to the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Only the English people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Only the English speaking people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 All Welsh people went to the chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well, there was a Welsh - church - lower down the valley. But - only the Welsh people living in that area went, there, that was in - betw
een Tylorstown and Pontygwaith, I think that's demolished now, that church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But in Tylorstown most of you went to the Welsh chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Or if they were English speaking they went to church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They went to - oh yes, the English church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Or would you say there were different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, I wouldn't think - no. Some were poorer than others of course, naturally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you think that one group felt superior to the rest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
I never found that that was - I don't know, to a certain extent I think - I think we thought we were - as good as anybody sort of thing you know and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were some families thought of as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Very little section. Very little section.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were others thought of as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, oh very respectable.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember a distinction of this kind at all between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, because you see they were all miners. All miners. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your mother and father have the same attitude towards people in different classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 All - you see were all working class, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But your mother and father didn't show any difference of attitude?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No. No. No.
 My mother was very kind to people, she would give money you know to people she thought were in need always. 'Cos years after she died I discovered there was somebody who was always having money from her. And which I never knew when she was alive and she 
never showed - that she gave it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No I don't think so. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another? To go from the working class say to the middle class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No I don't think - what I can always remember is - my mother was a wonderful ironer you know. And there was this brass rod there and all the clothes hanging. And there was a head - headmaster in Tylorstown, David Lace his name was,
 and he had an awful snob of a wife you know. And she did think she was a duchess you know and she used to have these gold chains down here you know and dress up, beautiful hats - and all this. They only had two children. Enid Williams, oh, and the brothe
r
. The brother lives in Port Talbot still I think, if he's still alive. But the - Enid became a lecturer in music in Bangor. Normal college. And Eleanor went you know to Bangor Normal. She was a lovely girl. And - had a tragic end you see. But her mother w
a
s a real snob and, a lawyer's daughter. The father was lovely man. And I can never forget my mother - and they loved coming up 'cos he was always very friendly with my father and used to talk for hours on all sorts of topics, and she would come and sit, y
o
u know, and very haw haw. And - look at - watch my mother ironing and all that and she would go up to the - feel the linen you know that was on the rod there. Oh, and it used to make my mother tamping mad, well it made her more mad when - one day, she was
 
ill and so my father said, well I mynd lawr i gweld hi. So she goes. And she never forgot for the rest of her life the bed that that woman lived in. Slept in. It was filthy. And she was able to go and - look at and feel my mother's beautiful - starched cl
othes. And - my mother - never forgot it. She said, yr hen uwch, she said, moyn tynnu dillad off I golchi nhw, she said. And she was beautifully dressed herself you see. But you know her brother is still living in Port Talbot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember anybody described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Well I - we used to think that these Fenwich family, that Mrs Fenwich was a real lady 'soc she was smart and handsome you know and nice - and beautifully dressed and - but I don't remember any others. The 
doctor's wife had died when we were young you see, the doctors - two doctors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why did you think Mrs Fenwick was a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Don't know. No Idea. She was smart and tall, handsome, nice looking. Beautifully dressed always. Oh yes, yes, comfortably off.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They were all farmers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 From - Hirwaun, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Let me see, yes, Bobby Forbes, the name of the Bobby was, there was only one policeman in Tylorstown. Bobby Forb
es, big big man he was. And the children -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you think of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We were a bit afraid of him I think. Yes, I think we were a bit afraid of him. But after that came a Mr - somebody who lived -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why were you afraid of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We always thought we had to be afraid of a policeman, it seemed to be a fancy, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Your mother never threatened you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No. There was another policeman - oh - but he lived in Church Street, not far from us after this Bobby Forbes had died.
 I can remember two policemen there but not more. And not ever be afraid of them. No, never been afraid of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But when you were little you were a little afraid of this policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes, yes, we - I think we would run if we saw them you know, run away, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How do you think they treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh very kind. I don't think they were very nasty. Don't ever recollect them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No. That was one thing - my father bought the house as soon as he was
 married. And it's strangely enough - the funny story about this is this that was just on my mind. He bought the house from a Mr and Mrs John who went to live down on the main road. They lived in it when it was newly built, and they went to live down the 
m
ain road, and they had one son. And he was so tall - that we called him Long John. And this is the strange thing, that when my mother died and we had the house up for sale - Mair lives in it you see after - after my mother died in - you know, she didn't l
ive at all, she was ready to come away after my mother died and we sold it the next day really - to this Long John. This man - whose parents were the original owners of the house. And he's still - and do you know -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No, we were never - we were - they - we were - oh and you see my father worked so hard, look what he used to do. Used to have his daily pay, from - weekly pay from work. He collected rents - for Doctor Morris y
ou see. And for a Mr S.H. Williams from Ferndale. And for Doctor Somebody - oh - in Apentre for another Doctor Thomas in Pentre. Well he used to have in discount you see for all the rents that he had. And then on top of that - he was - Secretary at the Ra
c
cobites, he had pay for that you see. He was also Secretary but he wasn't earning anything for that for the explosion fund. And do you know, he lived - to pay off - all the dependants of the explosion of - 18 - something you see, the explosion 1905, the e
x
plosion of 1905, he lived to pay off - everybody - compensation. But one. And that one - was what I'd been telling you about, Auntie Maggie. Auntie Maggie - was - the only living person - who had money because her parents - were dead. She - when her fathe
r
 died in the explosion and when her mother died they said Maggie was to have her money because she was T.B. And she had that money until she - until everybody else - now there was one man - living down at Swansea Valley who lived very old and he - when he
 died - my father - closed the account and bought an annuity for Maggie Phillips. And she lived and then the annuity died with her, so that it finished like that. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 So he had a lot of income from other sources?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - oh - several sources, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 So you were never really hard up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, never. Never knew what it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Your father wasn't ill or out of work was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Never. Never - never out of work you see. And never ill, he had very good health you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you remember any p
eople in the district that were disapproved of strongly and whether the people in Tylorstown showed their disapproval?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, I don't think so. The - we always - sort of looked down at people who went to drink and - got drunk and things like that you kn
ow, it was - oh yes. Though I was friendly - funnily enough I was friendly with - with the daughter of a public house, The Tylors Hotel, Tylorstown, it's still in existence, I don't know if - yes, it's still there. And it - oh, it's quite changed inside, 
and we - we shelter in the door - way when we're waiting on a bus to come by.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they look down on people who drank?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No. I don't think so, they were very friendly publicans you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about the people in Tylorstown, were there any people they sort of looked down on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No I never felt that. But the other hotel, Queens Square, was a very very big hotel. That has been demolished entirely. There's only one pub in Tylorstown now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were you ever given lessons by one of your parents, you went to school I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh we went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You don't remember how old you were when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I went to school at three and a half. My brother was five, 'cos we shouldn't go to school 'til you were five in t
hose days. My brother was five, and I suppose - that I cried so much - that my mother had to ask the headmistress would she take me. And I went to school when I was three and a half because I cried after my brother. Oh I've got lovely photos of myself. An
d do you know, that that - what do you call her - Rhiannon, is the living image -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 When you first started school what time of the morning would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh nine o'clock we started always. We were going out of the house about twenty to nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And when did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Oh - and we walked through the woods, beautiful woods, we used to kick through the - the leaves you know in the Autumn, we used to love it. All through a big wood we went to school. Come home to dinner. Back again afternoon 
and home for tea. And do you know I've lived to see - when I was a child there was - the pits wasn't sunk. I lived to see the pit sink - sunk - and a great big power station - built on the railway, you know, the other side of the railway, the railways in 
f
ront of it. I've lived to see this power station being built, and we never had to put a light in the bedroom because it was on - day and night, and there were no houses in front of us, it was down in the valley. I have lived now - remember - to see that e
ntirely demolished. And the grass is growing on the incline. And by next year there won't be any sign of any tip or incline. I used to go over that - river Taff,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How old were you starting afternoon school, you went all day straight away did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What kind of a school was it, a board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Belonged to the council you see, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Mixed or boys or girls?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Mixed. Mixed. Mixed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get to school, how long did it take you to walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 It was a good - ten minutes walk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who went with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We were with all the children together you see, a crowd of us, yes. Meredith would bring me in the beginning you see, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 At home, come home to dinner and go back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I loved it. I loved school. And my brother did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh, you had a - Mrs - we had a woman - who was a married woman you know in those days, Mrs Softwood her na
me was. And she - had a - didn't have a - was it Norah Southwood, yes, she'd one daughter, that's right. And - oh she was savage, we were afraid - really afraid of her you know. She was really quite savage. And there was another one - Alice Kingdom her na
me was, but she became a Mrs Jones. And her son -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What made you think the first one savage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - she was - sharp you know, oh and she loved the stick. We got a crack for - for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Talking when we weren't supposed to talk. It would always be me talking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 A cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Yes. A cane, you'd have a cane, yes, yes. But mind I won't say - didn't have the cane many times, it must have been something very wrong if I had a cane, I was terrified of the cane, I think it only once I ever had it and I thought it was terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they emphasise certain things as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Don't remember - nothing about that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Not about the way you spoke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. Oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Tidiness, punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh punctuality oh we were always punctual. Oh good gracious me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen, how would they punish the children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - turn your back and go in the corner. Turn your back on the class you know, pushed in the
 corner and turn your back and not to move you know. Terrible wasn't it, when you think of it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they punish the girls the same as the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you have to do to be punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh you go in the corner, that's all - oh I don
't remember that you see, talking I expect with me. I was always having it. I remember - one or two of my reports. Much too talkative in class. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes, they made sure that we did it, did our homework.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Oh I don't think so, I don't remember them - you know, querying us at all 'cos we - they they knew we brought our homework home and did it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We had
 our leather bags. Never. Never - don't think my - only once, my mother ever went to school and she was cross. Because one of the teachers smacked my brother. And marked his hand with a cane, and she went down and told her what she thought about her, but 
I don't remember anything much about it. Meredith it was you see. Remember him having a nasty smack, remember Meredith having a smack on his hand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents ever meet the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, I don't think we - they were people who lived near us and we knew them you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did the other children come from similar types of home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, we were all more working class homes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't know, yes, some -
 children were favourites you know. Like the - like the woman in the bake-house. Out of the way, and John Davis' children. But - children they tended to favour some children you know. Depends who they were you see. People like us you see, we were - bit fa
vourite you see to the teachers all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't remember gangs at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were there any children in school who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 'Cos we were all in our little pack who used to go to scho
ol together you see through these woods. Oh we used to love picking up acorns on the way. No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You don't remember any children who were left out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. I don't. No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you go on to another school afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I went straight to that Tylorstown school to Ferndale Secondary you see. Ferndale Secondary school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How old were you when you went there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What time would you have to go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh, as I tell you we had to walk - in the morning we had
 a good - mile and a half to walk you see. We used to start out about half past eight I think to go to Ferndale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you walk all the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 All the way, there were no trams or anything. And we used to meet this Miss Owen, Lydia Owen, oh she was lovely.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 She lived on the way to school did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 She was lodging you see in - in this place, she used to come down and wait for \{ILLEGIBLE\}
 we used to walk all the way catching hands you know, all the way to Ferndale together she was lovely. She's still alive you know. I must go and see her this summer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You didn't come home in the lunch hour then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No, no, no, we took our - and do you know, there - there were no such things as serviettes in those days were there, nice big handkerchief i
t was you know that would be put to the bread and butter would be put in a lovely big handkerchief you see, the pure linen handkerchiefs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What would you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you know, I've got not much recollection about that. What would be in there, in that - sandwiches, I don't remember anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who would go with you to school then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - there was my brother and I you see and Gwladys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Meredith?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, Gwladys didn't - because - she left school - the - the - the third, she left school t
o go into a - a tailoress to learn - dressmaking, so she had to make our clothes for us you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 So it was only you and Meredith?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And you'd be walking and you'd meet this teacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. At the bottom, yes, yes, oh she was lovely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you think of Ferndale school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I loved school you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What did you think about the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 As I said I saw somebody the other day that I haven't seen since I was twenty-two years of age, and she remembered me you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you feel about the teachers in Ferndale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Well you see, I was tended always to be a bit of a favourite. There was Mr Humphries, Maerdy. Nellie - there was Nellie and - no, we enjoyed it, we loved school you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they emphasize some things, did you have punishment there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I had to write many lines, I must not talk, I must not talk, I must not talk, that was a punishment, yes, write lines.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents show interest in your schoolwork there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes, they were - well they made sure that we did our work. Or homework. We shouldn't go out -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they ever visit Ferndale?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would the children in Ferndale school come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, more or less, they were all miners you see and - people in offices and things and preachers and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were there any gangs or groups in school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't remember in Ferndale Secondary you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would teachers single out some - children for different treatment from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No, they were - do you know what I can remember quite well? There was a picture on the wall, I can see it now as if it was yesterday, look how many years I'm going back. That picture - I don't know who it's by, I must look now - when I go ho
me - when did you last see your father? And do you know these two teachers that were sort of - invigilating - were having a good bit of fun on that picture and I was - neglecting my work through listeneing - why - well what were they laughing at you know,
 I couldn't see there was anything to laugh in it you see. When did you last see your father? Yes, and I was busy - looking at that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How old were you when you left Ferndale school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I never left it really until I - you see I went straight to college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were you eighteen when you went to college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You had to be eighteen didn't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Then you went straight to college?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Barry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 For two years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Two years in Barry, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No I didn't, I had a very happy time in Barry college, the only silly thing I did there was - what did I do - I fell. I can remember being made an awful fuss of. I fell on my elbow. Oh, and I had a bad elbow - through playing hockey. Oh - and they all mad
e such a fuss of me. There was I going round - with my arm in a sling feeling very important. In Barry college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 And do you know what I can remember that Mr Lewis. Oh he was lovely. And do you know
 what I can remember too, sir Owen M. Edwards. Never forget. And I was telling Lady Edwards just the other day - when she was here the last time - he came to our final exam you know, Sir Owen M. Edwards, he wasn't Sir then, he was Own M. Edwards. And - we
 
had an inspection, you see, we used to have inspections with certain subjects, and - only a certain few would be chosen to represent certain sections of the - of the class. And - Sir Owen was coming to examine us in - recitation you see. And - and reading
. And I can see him now coming to that room with Eleanor and \endash 
 you know, because she was the Welsh - Welsh mistress, I was a big favourite with her. She was very very kind to me. And - until - she died I was friendly with her. I was sorry she died you know 
so soon. She had cancer terrible, she suffered terribly. She - come - brings him into our - classroom A you know and I was sitting there, and Lil Morris sat - Lil Morris it was sitting behind me. And she was a devil, she was always poking me in the back y
o
u know. Always poking - seats were going up like that in steps you know - in Barry college, they're still there. And - she'd be poking me in the back and - there was Sir Owen looking round, looking at this list you see. And it was alphabetical order. And 
t
he first name chosen was me. Oh, I could feel now - I could feel now my heart going that bad, and Lil Morris giving me - dig in the ribs, as much as to say, you - you've had it you see. The walk out the front and then he was going round the list and - few
 
more, right, we were taken out, only four of us you know, of course I had to be one of these four. We go out - into another room, classroom C it was. And we were sat now and Sir Owen came in with Eleanor Ellis. Principal headmistress, Miss Roe our Princip
a
l was like a Queen of England, she was handsome woman. English person you know. She'd come from England there which was very funny thing for the Barry. Glamorgan apparently had chosen this woman you know. Lhere were a lot of Welsh people jealous at the ti
m
e. Oh but she was handsome. I used to worry about her now too. She - but first of all about this exam - examination, so we go into this classroom and there is Sir Owen. Oh, and my heart was going pitter-pat, pitter-pat you know. And - Sir Owen had us look
i
ng down this list - and he said, looked at me, called my name out. Lizze Ann Davis. And - most of them didn't know I was Lizzie Ann you see. Betty everybody had called me. My college mother christened me Betty. In the - in the bucket of water. And - he sa
i
d, well now - D'yw am I chi ddarllen rhywbeth a d'yw a chi adrodd rhywbeth - yn Gmyraeg neu yn Saesneg, newch beth chi likio. Well there was so - dewiswch un 'o'r dau yn Saesneg ar llath yn Gymraeg, he said, oh he was very nice. So I thought, oh well here
 
goes. Welsh first. And here's me choosing the easiest thing I'd learnt, you know, and my nerves went. Mae John yn mynd I Lundain. Now something in English. And my English was this. Oh His Blindness, by Milton. Well he said, I'm very pleased, he said, and 
-
 I'm sure you'll be pleased to know - that you have all gone up a mark. And I don't remember a mark, whether we went up to an A plus instead of being A, something like that it was. And so everybody's mark went up because I had - done so well apparently yo
u know. Oh, I shall never forget it and imagine all these years I've remember that and I haven't said it for years now. My native land, be there a man, so - we had to learn so - about a hundred lines you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 While you were at school you didn't have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
The first time I ever earned anything and I was very proud of that - was after I came out of college - and there was a strike of miners. And my father - had to work extra hard. An
d he took me into the office - to work in the office and I - that's the first bit of money I earned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That would be 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, and walk - I walked - oh these two miles to Ferndale to this office you see and taking our - lunch with us. And that was when I -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Your first job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 In school you mean? Oh, after I left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You didn't have a job when you were in school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, no. No, no, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You did this little job in the office to help your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That's right. That's right. Yes, that's all. In the holidays, that's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What exactly did you have to do, how long did you work for, was it a few months?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, only a few weeks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You don't remember what you had to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 In my holidays. No I don't remember anything about the money. I don't suppose I had any money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Pocket money was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, I expect. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What was your first full time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Teaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That was in 1918 you started wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You started straight away did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Oh yes, I started straight away. I'm trying to remember now where - I was - I was in infants. That's right, I went straight to Hendreargoed school. Out of college. And there was a Miss Davis, a headmistress, Pitsey Davis and she
 was from Pontrhydyfen originally. And she was a tartar. Oh - oh, it was real hard labour. She had a friend who lived with her, she was a Miss Riesman she was under head teacher. And they always went -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What age children did you teach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I started 
in a - what they call a first class. No, I'm wrong. I started in the baby's class. I was there for a year and then I went to the first class. And those would be the top class in the school see, there was no standard one, and there I remained until I - got
 married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
But I was very lucky you see, I wasn't a good piano player but I could play the piano. And I could play hymns, play for dancing - for the kids, so that I had quite a lot of time off from my class to play for the
 other teachers 'cos there was nobody else who could play. And I was not much good mind but I used to do it. And this girl that's in Whitchurch now, Edith - she was on the staff. And - she was at the first class you see, Edith, and she was a very good tea
c
her too. Edith Powell her name was in those days. And now she did have a nice singing voice. So - I've been trying to stuff this into her, talking about her, about these things, but oh it's hopeless to get through to her - about the fun you know, she has 
l
aughed you know when I mentioned this. She used - had a lovely singing voice, soprano, and she used to sing in chapel and all this and - after dinner, see we'd have our lunch in school and after dinner we'd go round the piano and the headmistress was in t
h
e room, she wouldn't hear us you see. It was long way up, beautiful new school, brand new, a lovely big hall. And she - and these concerts - celebrity concerts would be in Cardiff and we'd all go there you see, and I can always remember Galli-curci coming
 
- you know, to Cardiff, and we learnt all those - what are their names now - what was that tenor's name, oh - all the important - Gigli and all those that came to the - old Empire, it's - it's gone out existence long ago and a shop's there now. It's years
 
and years ago. Well we used to go to these concerts you see, and then on the Monday in school we'd be - I'd be the pianist and she would be - the artiste, Edith you know, and she'd sing like this you see, and the old - head wouldn't hear us in the other -
 other end of the school. We used to have the time of our lives. And I used to pretend that I was a great pianist and I wasn't a great pianist at all, but Edith - could sing you know. And often think.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get the job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Only applied you se
e to the council, well it automatically came to you you see with - there weren't many people going to college in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What hours did you work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Nine to twelve. And two - two to half past three in the infants. We were out at half past three
. And we used to have a lot of - of time, I was trying to - get awake to an existence and - laughing about it. She did laugh about it. Last time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you have holiday with pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, yes, August holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You don't remember what you were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No idea. Oh only about eight pound a month it was when we started I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you feel it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Don't think it ever bothered me. I gave it straight to my mother. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You don't know what it was spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I gave my money to my mother all the years until I went to college. - Until I - got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What was it spent on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 On the household food you see and things.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get on with the other people in the school that you worked with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 O
h very well, I can - oh dear, dear, oh I - I can remember all the teachers in - round the classes. Now Bessie who was in - all dead. And strangely enough they're all dead but that Edith and me. We're the only two left.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get on with the head?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Let's see now, the other one is dead. Yes, she's died. Now what's her name now, oh dear, Marion -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you get on with the headmistress?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh we had our little ups and downs you know, she used to think I was a bit cheeky. 'Cos I'd answe
r her back and nobody else would be afraid to answer her back. But I - I never believed in being down trodden you know. Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I loved teaching you see, I - loved teaching before I ever went into teaching.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What jobs have you done since the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Nothing, only - in the Post Office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That would be in about 1940 something wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 '40, yes, '42.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You took over a Post Office then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You moved to Cardiff from Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you like that very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Oh I loved it. Oh I loved it. And my husband loved it too you know, he liked it. He loved the work, and he was good you know, really good at figures until - we had a horrible experience of that burglar you know, coming in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You had to serve a two year training period for the teaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you belong to a professional organization?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Only the NUT.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you take part in any of the activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I used to go to the meetings. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you feel that your employers and the workers had the same interests?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't think it disturbed me at all, I never bothered.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 It's rather different in a school really isn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would you say that full time work changed your general attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No, I don't think so. You see, I'd always said I was going to be a teacher, and I loved it and it never bothered me. Loved going to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You didn't change at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No. No. No. And my sister next to me, she was made to be a dressmaker to make clothes for us. And she always, you know, be - and after that she used to grumble, she says, oh I always had to stay home to look after you lot. 'Cos all the rest went to Second
ary school you see, after her. Every one of them. She was the only one, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 She felt it did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
She did. But it was good for her you see 'cos - she's now seventy-two you see. No, she doesn't bother with sewing now but she'll do anything, if you wanted her to turn a hem up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But she really wanted to go on in school did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No, she didn't you see. No, no, she didn't, no, she was rather a nervous type. No, she wasn't fond of school, so she was quite glad to be a dressmaker, of course she's - trained properly with a - with a tailoress, who went out to Australia you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you continue to live at home after you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You went to college to Barry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That's right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You were coming home just holiday times?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh - that's right, yes. No, no, only holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your relationship with your parents change then at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We were all very happy, very friendly like we still are you see, all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you spend your Sundays any differently then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Cwrdd trwy'r dydd.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about in Barry when you went to college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Cwrdd trwy'r dydd. Yes. Yes, I went three times on a Sunday. We had to go once you see, but I went because I was
 friendly with the Jones' and I went to tea every Sunday with them you see. And then I went back to college.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You knew people in Barry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I only met them through this - D. L. Davis telling me, cer I siarad Davy Jones, chi n'abod fi, ef yn gefnder i
 fi, you see that's how I met them, otherwise I wouldn't have been. I'd have been properly -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They were people with connections from Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 That's why the other girls never went to Sunday school you see, in Barry. But Ellen Evans was a membe
r of Pennywell Barry, so she was - we went you know. I remember us having a row once for talking in chapel too as well, going back to coll, we were put on the carpet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they like you to go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes. You had to go once. Yes, yes. Oh I went to Sunday school and chapel in the night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about when you were home on holiday then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh, cwrdd libanus in Tylorstown then. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 It wouldn't change?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I wasn't intereste
d in politics at all but because my father was a Liberal - I was a Liberal, and I once worked for a Liberal candidate who didn't win the seat because a Labour always went in the Rhondda you see. And I remember this Liberal - I wasn't paid for my work eith
er, I remember that. Did it for nothing. Forget his name now too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 So you were interested then in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Not - not on - that I would - was considered myself a Liberal, I wasn't terribly interested in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why do you think you were a Liberal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Because my father was a Liberal. That's all. It didn't mean anything more than that to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you vote in an election?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Whenever there was an election I voted and if I - didn't vote Liberal I'd choose the next best evil. Whichever it was
. Mostly Labour. If I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were you a member of a political party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But you did work once for the Liberal party you say?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 None at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 How would you spend your spare time when you were in college and when you started teaching, would you do different things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Well as I said we went to cwrdd every night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 It was still the same really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. The same.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You didn't change your ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You went out in the evenings to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Chapel, that's all, ooh you didn't go out anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Who would you go with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 The rest of the family, the children, the rest of us, we all went together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you make any new friends then, boys or girls?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
No. No. No, my brother had friends you know and he would take us and we'd go on outings - to Ostribechga and things like that, we walked miles you know, wonderful for walking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you ever bring friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, no, people would call, my father used to - my mother used to say, mae rhaid i pawb dod yma, but we didn't caf\'e9
, we could take who we liked home. They were very very sociable my parents. My father always had somebody you see, the Rac
cobites in. And I always remember the family - Mr and Mrs Tommy Davis, Ferndale, he was a big Raccobie and they only had Gwyndridd - Gwyndridd Davis and - only son they had and - he - they used to come to our house you see but we never went up there becau
se there were too many. But that Gwyndridd Davis is that - what you call it's - Gwen - now what's her -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Which time do you mean now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 After you left school and when you were in college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, this Uessie Hughes and Bessie Griffiths they were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Were they from Tylorstown?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, Tylorstown. Well Bessie Hughes was living in Ferndale. But she was teaching on our staff you see. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Girls they were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Where would you go with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
Oh - they were Baptists but I was - I was Methodist - Presbyterian you see so - no, we wouldn't have an out much, only go on hikes on the weekends. We'd go for hikes on Saturdays. Down to Ostravesta and up Aberdare mountain and things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 What about when the weather was bad or in the winter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Stay at home and read. That was our hobby, reading, reading, reading.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 But you did go to Cardiff occasionally to a concert?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We went to that celebrity concert you know, but it would be only on a Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Would they be very often?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, not very often. They were in the old Empire you see, at Christmas. Oh, I heard Balli-curci, Paderevski - Madam - Madam -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Patti?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, no, I never heard her, she was - bef
ore my time. Galli-curci - oh, what was that wonderful man now what do they say now - Gigli, and the other one, Paderevski, playing that piano, I'll never forget him. Never forget him playing that piano. He played in the darkness you know, only a very ver
y low light he had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents meet your friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Only when they came to the house.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did your parents expect to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 My mother would often - my father - my mother would often say, what's this, mai digon yma a chi'n
 dod rhagor, you know she used to say, but my father was always pleased to have a crowed of us. Much more jolly than my mother my father was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You were closer to your father were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 I don't know, much the same, but my father - liked a fuss wher
e my mother was - used to think we were quite enough without having any more - crowds more in. But we - crowds we brought them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did they like to know where you were in the period after you'd left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They wanted to know where you were going and who you were with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 
And a great thrill we had was to have the house next door you know. Door made into next door for us to sleep next door, 'cos they wanted another bedroom you see. Oh - and we had that for years. And we - 
you go down a step 'cos it was down a greet, you had to go down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You still had that when you were in college?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They still had that when I was in coll, yes. Yes, it was great fun. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you have to be in by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 We never h
ad any - 'cos you see when we were in chapel we always went straight home from chapel. Yes. We never - we sometimes walked up and down. There used to be a fashion in those days of walking to Ferndale, but not on Sundays, and walking back you know, in the 
sunny weather, walking the roads in Ferndale, not in Tylorstown. Nothing in Tylorstown see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 You would do that would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Yes. Yes, walk up and down the road with friends. Same lot, the girls that we had you see in - in coll. It was a funny habit 
wasn't it, walking up and down the road. Nothing else to - that's right, yes, must have been.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Did you ever take any boys home then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No. Didn't take the boys home, we never showed we met the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 Don't know, but parents would never want us to bring boys home. We - we had enough of our own. Coming in and out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13510004 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 They didn't mind you taking girls home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2432619 DT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7092875\charrsid12417786 No, no.
\par }}